item.title: Meet Nick
item.dc:creator: jarome
item.content:encoded:
[vc_row id="section-3745" el_class="container"][vc_column][vc_row_inner][vc_column_inner width="1/2"][vc_raw_html]JTNDaDIlM0VJbiUyMGhpcyUyMHJvb2tpZSUyMHllYXIlMkMlMjBOaWNrJTIwY2xhaW1lZCUyMHNpeCUyMHJhY2UlMjB3aW5zJTIwYW5kJTIwc2Vjb25kJTIwaW4lMjB0aGUlMjBjaGFtcGlvbnNoaXAuJTIwVGhlJTIwaGlnaGVzdCUyMHBsYWNpbmclMjBvZiUyMGFueSUyMHJvb2tpZS4lM0MlMkZoMiUzRQ==[/vc_raw_html][/vc_column_inner][vc_column_inner width="1/2"][vc_column_text]Nick Percat started racing karts at the age of seven. He progressed into car racing in 2005, at the age of 16, competing in Formula Ford in South Australia. In 2006, Nick raced Aussie Racing cars, his first attempt at racing in front of the Supercar teams. In his rookie year, Nick claimed six race wins and second in the championship – the highest placing of any rookie. In October 2006, Nick was approached by Tom Walkinshaw and placed on a contract with the iconic Holden Racing team. Nick was supported by Walkinshaw Racing throughout 2007–2014. During this time, Nick progressed through Formula Ford in 2007–2009, winning the Australian championship in 2009 and re-writing many records along the way. 2010 Nick made his debut into Supercar racing, competing for Jay Motorsport. During his rookie year he scored seven podiums and was promoted to a factory run Walkinshaw racing car for 2011, supported by Coates Hire. In May 2011, the Holden Racing team announced Nick would be partnering Garth Tander for the endurance races at Phillip Island and Bathurst. Nick was a rookie to Bathurst in Supercars. In the 2011 Bathurst 1000, Nick became the first rookie in 23 years to win the largest motor race in Australia. It was also the closest finish in the history of the race.[/vc_column_text][/vc_column_inner][/vc_row_inner][/vc_column][/vc_row][vc_row id="section-4046" el_class="white-background video-player-container"][vc_column][vc_row_inner el_class="container-small"][vc_column_inner][vc_video link="https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=9RDPN9IeXRc"][/vc_column_inner][/vc_row_inner][/vc_column][/vc_row][vc_row id="section-7486" el_class="white-background"][vc_column][vc_row_inner el_class="container-small"][vc_column_inner width="1/2"][vc_column_text]

2016

[/vc_column_text][/vc_column_inner][vc_column_inner width="1/2"][vc_column_text]2016 Nick claimed his first solo Supercar win. This win came in front of his home crowd in Adelaide, at the Clipsal 500. In torrential conditions, Nick drove his LD Motorsport car to top spot by race end. This was LD Motorsport's first race win. At the Bathurst 1000, Nick finished third, giving LD Motorsport its first Bathurst 1000 podium. Nick finished the season strongly at the Coates Hire Sydney 500 by qualifying in the top 10 shootout. This was LD Motorsport's first top 10 shootout.[/vc_column_text][/vc_column_inner][/vc_row_inner][vc_row_inner el_class="container-small"][vc_column_inner width="1/2"][vc_column_text]

2014

[/vc_column_text][/vc_column_inner][vc_column_inner width="1/2"][vc_column_text]2014 Nick made his debut into the main Supercar series with Walkinshaw Racing. His car continued to be supported by Coates Hire. Nick instantly made a big impact in the Supercar scene securing two podiums, second at Sydney Motorsport Park and third at Bathurst 1000. On the 24th of December 2014, it was announced that Nick would contest the V8 Supercars 2015 season with Lucas Dumbrell Motorsport after Walkinshaw Racing failed to find the necessary budget to run Nick's car. This was the end of Nick's contract with Walkinshaw Racing, which began in 2006.[/vc_column_text][/vc_column_inner][/vc_row_inner][vc_row_inner el_class="container-small"][vc_column_inner width="1/2"][vc_column_text]

2013

[/vc_column_text][/vc_column_inner][vc_column_inner width="1/2"][vc_column_text]2013 Nick Moved into the Porsche Carrera Cup with the backing of Coates Hire. With no seats available in the Supercar championship, Nick looked to Porsche to prove he had what it took in another category. Nick took the Porsche grid by surprise by claiming pole position on debut and re-setting the Clipsal 500 Porsche lap record in the process. In 2013, Nick went on to claim five round wins, multiple pole positions and five lap records, to finish a hard-fought second in the championship behind Porsche legend Craig Baird.[/vc_column_text][/vc_column_inner][/vc_row_inner][vc_row_inner el_class="container-small"][vc_column_inner width="1/2"][vc_column_text]

2012

[/vc_column_text][/vc_column_inner][vc_column_inner width="1/2"][vc_column_text]2012 Nick continued in the Development Supercar series with Walkinshaw racing and Coates Hire support. He also retained his drive with the Holden Racing team alongside Tander. The 2012 Development Supercar series was a battle between Nick, Scott Mclaughlin, Chaz Mostert and Scott Pye. All four drivers were racing for factory teams that dominated the season in one of the tightest battles the DVS series has seen. Mclaughlin, Pye and Mostert secured drives in the main Supercar series for 2013.[/vc_column_text][/vc_column_inner][/vc_row_inner][/vc_column][/vc_row]

item.title: Townsville Preview
item.dc:creator: adam
item.content:encoded: Hi Everyone, We’re approaching the halfway mark in the Supercars championship by heading north for the Townsville 400 this weekend! It’s one of my favourite tracks. Even though it’s a street track, I’d describe it as more of a combination of the traditional Adelaide-style street track and Albert Park grand prix circuits. It’s a bit of a hybrid of flowing corners and ninety degree corners and big kerbs. I qualified on the front row for the first time ever in a Supercar at Townsville in my rookie year in 2014, and made my first Top 10 shootout appearance that same year. I’ve also won there in Dunlop Super2 and Carrera Cup, but the last couple of years I’ve had a few DNFs, so I’m certainly looking to turn my Townsville luck back around. I scored my first podium of the year and my first with BJR at the recent round in Darwin, which was a great reward for all the hard work the team has put in this year. A trouble-free round has also meant a pretty smooth turnaround for the crew. We’ve got some more new bits on my car which we will trial in Friday practice. I think it will be a very interesting event. We’ve graded it as one of the harder places on tyres, so we could see more of the tyre issues that surfaced at Phillip Island earlier in the season. The circuit layout is hard on the left rear tyre because there’s a lot of long loaded corners where we are at 100% throttle and sliding the cars. I’m preparing to have to adjust the way that I drive the car to prevent any tyre failures. It’s cool to have a new sponsor, McHitch, on the livery of Car 8 for this event. They are a family run business, and BJR are a family run team so there is a good synergy there. Since Darwin I’ve had a bit of a break. I’ve spent some quality time at home, making sure the dogs are behaving. Nelson has somehow mastered the art of removing a plant out of the pot without also removing the soil, so he can eat it. Bunnings are getting their money’s worth out of me with replacement plants! It’s also been announced recently that Macauley Jones will co-drive with me in the endurance races. He’s doing a solid job in the Dunlop Super2 series, and I look forward to watching him race in Townsville as well this weekend. Remember you can follow me on social media for updates across the event. Twitter- @nickpercat Instagram - @nickpercat

item.title: Coates Hire Ipswich SuperSprint Preview
item.dc:creator: nick
item.content:encoded:
Hi Everyone,
After our most recent Supercars event in Townsville, we head back to Queensland this weekend for the Coates Hire Ipswich SuperSprint. It’s an important one for me because Coates Hire is one of my long time personal sponsors. They’ve been behind me since 2011, so I want to put on a good show for their staff and customers who come out to the races.<!--more-->
I’ve been fairly busy in the couple of weeks between rounds. Last weekend I competed in round 4 of the Australian Karting Championships in Emerald, North Queensland.
It was the first time the Emerald Go Kart Club has hosted a national level competition, and like many of the drivers there, it was my first time racing at that track. I finished 6th in the final race, and overall had a really enjoyable weekend.
Because I’m in the middle of a crazy six-week period of travel and racing, I had to send the dogs to stay with my mum and dad in Adelaide for a few weeks. Needless to say, my mum has her hands full looking after two Labradors AND their dog Ali, but I think everyone is coping well. And something tells me that Doug and Nelson are being spoilt rotten!
There is an additional drivers practice session this Friday at Queensland Raceway, and again my endurance co-driver Macauley Jones will get some laps in Car 8. Brad Jones Racing is still chasing its first race win and podium at Queensland Raceway, so it would be awesome to help change that statistic for the team!
We are running a bright new livery this weekend, with support from Dunlop Super Dealers. I think it looks great, and would almost go so far as to say it’s my favourite livery of the ones we’ve run this season.
Speaking of new shiny things, I’ve recently launched this new website. It has some great features and is compatible with mobile devices so even if you’re on the go, check it out!
Remember you can follow me on social media for updates across the event.
Twitter- @nickpercat Instagram - @nickpercat Facebook- Nick Percat

item.title: Coates Hire Supersprint
item.dc:creator: nick
item.content:encoded: SATURDAY THE WORD FROM NICK Nick and the Dunlop Super Dealer team did a great job moving forward today. A penalty on another driver saw Nick jump up the starting order from 11th to 10th, and from there he was set to charge. Nick had great pace and was able to manage his tyres really well, making moves on those in front with confidence to finish the 120 kilometre race in 7th. “Qualifying wasn’t the result we wanted but we had made some changes after practice and improved it. I had two laps to make it work and I feel like one more probably could have put us further up the order like we should have been.” “The Dunlop Super Dealer was quite fast on track today, my pace was good and I was able to do a few lunges on people and move forward a couple of spots around the track so overall I’m happy. The guys in the pits did a really good job today on all cars and my engineer Paul has given me a great car setup.” “Having 2 Brad Jones Racing cars in the top ten today is a solid result for the team and we’re looking forward to seeing what more we can do tomorrow.” Saturday Qualified: 10th – 1:09.0489s Pole Position: Scott McLaughlin – 1:08.8167s Race Fifteen – 120kms/39 Laps Finished: 7th Winner: Scott McLaughlin   SUNDAY   THE WORD FROM NICK The Dunlop Super Dealer Commodore was running strong in the top ten in today’s 200kms race, making it as high as 5th. However with less than 15 laps to go, Nick, James Courtney and Garth Tander all came across debris on the circuit which forced them into the pits for tyres. The safety car made its first appearance of the weekend to remove the debris, and the race resumed with 8 laps to go. With Nick rejoining 26th and a lap down, he didn’t have enough time to gain back the positions he would have liked. However Nick managed to get in front of the cars in front who were also a lap down to claim 24th.   “I’m obviously disappointed for the team today. We had the chance to have The Dunlop Super Dealer and Freightliner Racing Commodore score top ten finishes in both yesterdays and todays’ race and take away a really good points haul.” “I can’t believe the amount of potential we have, but something out of anyone’s control has caught us out today. The Dunlop team came down straight away and were pretty gutted as well, they’ve had nothing but great feedback about this car and how good it looks all weekend. It would have been awesome for them and all the guys and girls at BJR to get the result I feel we deserved today.” Qualified: 8th – 1:08.9493s Pole Position: Scott McLaughlin – 1:08.4208s Race Sixteen – 200kms/65 Laps Finished: 24th Winner: Chaz Mostert

item.title: Sydney Motorsport Park Preview
item.dc:creator: nick
item.content:encoded:
We head to Sydney Motorsport Park this weekend for the final hit out before the endurance season commences.<!--more--> Sydney Motorsport Park (SMP) is a track I really like. I had my first individual podium result there in 2014; finishing second when Scotty McLaughlin and I drag raced to the finish line!
I think we’re in for another interesting weekend, particularly with the soft tyre on quite an abrasive surface. SMP is very hard on tyres and normally we see a lot of degradation here. Qualifying will be key here. You typically only get one lap to do a quick time on each set of tyres because the degradation is so high. During the races the job is to be mindful not to lean on them too hard or too early, or you can find yourself with bigger issues towards the end of the race.
It’s good to be representing a new sponsor on Car 8 in ACDelco this weekend. I think the metallic blue livery will look really good on the track. We’re going to give my enduro co-driver Macauley Jones some more laps in my car during Friday’s practice. Obviously he didn’t get much of an opportunity at Queensland Raceway with the engine failure, and at Winton the co-driver session was wet, so we want to get him comfortable and refine his seating position. He’s on double duties this weekend, running in the Dunlop Super2 series as well so the more laps the better for the young guy. Since the last round at Ipswich I went to Bali with one of my sponsors Timken. It was a great four-day getaway for a conference Timken were presenting at, and a nice escape from Melbourne’s winter weather. I also raced in the City of Melbourne titles go kart race. There was a huge turnout, with 50 entries in my class alone! I threw myself in the deep end, running a kart and an engine package I’d never used before. I had to learn quickly from that first practice session, but I ran inside the top four all weekend so that was cool.
I enjoy the challenge of driving different things, I feel it gives me a broader knowledge and helps me adapt to changing race conditions better. Hopefully the karting has helped me prepare for this weekend, especially as the Eastern Creek track changes so much. On the Monday after the Red Rooster Sydney SuperSprint we have a sponsor ride day. It’s always fun to scare lots of sponsors and give them a cool memory to remember! (It’d be awesome if we also had a trophy or two to show off… fingers crossed!)

item.title: Sydney Motorsport Park
item.dc:creator: nick
item.content:encoded:
A Word from Nick:<!--more-->
The middle stint was tough for us, we were caught behind Winterbottom and around this place it really hurts your tyres. I knew we had a good, fast car so after our second stop we came out in clear air and started to chip away at those front guys.
The guys came across the radio in those final laps telling me I needed to save fuel. In the final lap they said to use the buffer we had to the car behind as there was a good chance we weren’t going to make it otherwise. So the whole last lap I used about 20% throttle and rolled my way home. We actually ran completely out of fuel over the line and needed a little push back to the pits by Tim Slade!
Today’s result is an awesome credit to the guys and girls in the team. We had an issue with the car yesterday and the guys worked hard to find and fix it overnight and get us back up where we needed to be. These guys just don’t give up, they are pure racers and continue to work hard to get me up the front. I am leaving Sydney pretty happy with what we’ve achieved today and looking forward to getting into the endurance races ahead.
Qualified: 8th – 1:28.9192s Pole Position: Scott McLaughlin – 1:28.2259s Race 18 – 200kms / 52 Laps Finished: 6th Winner: Jamie Whincup

item.title: SANDOWN 500
item.dc:creator: nick
item.content:encoded:
THE WORD FROM NICK / MACAULEY
For the Mongrel Boots Racing duo of Nick Percat and Macauley Jones, their Pirtek Endurance Cup did not get off to the start they were hoping for.<!--more--> They lined up on the starting grid in a promising position of 10th, and were keen to move their way forward to the top 5. After a big accident on lap one saw Taz Douglas hit the tyre barrier hard at turn 6, the race was red flagged for over half an hour until the tyre barrier was fixed, then racing resumed. With the race being declared time certain, teams hustled to look at new strategies.
Macauley stayed in for 56 of the 127 laps, and then handed over to Nick for the final stint. About 10 laps into his stint Nick was reporting bad vibrations in the front left of the Mongrel Boots Commodore. With safety being a priority, the team pitted Nick twice to check for any potential issues. They had him in the garage for quite some time, and whilst they had completed 75% of the race distance, they sent Nick back out so he could claim any points on offer. He re-joined a number laps down and finished in 23rd position. They are keen to put the weekend behind them and turn their focus towards the biggest race of the year – the Bathurst 1000.

item.title: BATHURST 1000
item.dc:creator: nick
item.content:encoded:
A Word from Nick / Macauley<!--more-->
THE RESULT - Bathurst 1000 / 161 Laps Finished: DNF Winner: David Reynolds / Luke Youlden 2nd : Scott Pye / Warren Luff 3rd : Fabian Coulthard / Tony D’Alberto
THE WORD FROM NICK / MACAULEY It was a testing day for all at Mount Panorama today. The rain began at the start of the race, and only eased for the final 30 laps. This is where the day got really interesting. The team made the call to pit Nick and they were the first to go onto slicks. It was a huge risk considering the rain clouds were still looming, but one by one, all the other cars pitted for slicks and the race was on. The Boost Commodore was fixing for a podium position, but after a lockup going into the chase one of the tyres was badly flatspotted, making the car difficult to drive. Nick was in 11th on the final lap when the steering went heavy and he found himself in the wall. It was a heartbreak considering 997 of the 1000 kilometres had been completed. The team had done an outstanding job all weekend, but Bathurst as it so brutally can, crushed the winning dream today.
Macauley “As Bathurst always does, it had some ups and downs from today. We had really good car speed in the tricky conditions, especially with the amount of time we spent racing in the rain.” “I felt really good in the car in the first couple of stints and was slowly tuning it as we went along. I then handed it back to Nick for a huge stint and he did such a good job and really worked his way through the field.” “The car was fast, had great potential, and it was definitely a case of what could have been today, as it always is with Bathurst. I enjoyed the high of winning the 250km Super2 race yesterday, and the low of being oh so close to finishing today. The mountain always provides a challenge, and we’ll continue to come back for more.”
COMING UP Round 12 of the Virgin Australia Supercars Championship Gold Coast 600 – Final Round of the Pirtek Endurance Cup! 20-22 October 2017 Surfers Paradise, Queensland

item.title: GOLD COAST 600
item.dc:creator: nick
item.content:encoded:
A word from Nick / Macauley <!--more--> TODAYS TIMES Qualifying Qualified: 14th – 1:11.1837 Provisional Pole Position: Shane Van Gisbergen – 1:10.3701 Top Ten Shootout Pole Position: Shane Van Gisbergen Race 22 – 300kms / 102 Laps Finished: 10th Winner: Scott McLaughlin & Alex Premat
THE WORD FROM NICK
'' I am happy with our top 10 result for the final race of the enduro cup. It has been a tough endurance season for the whole team and this weekend we have taken many positives. The pace in the wet yesterday was fantastic and the dry today the car had more then enough speed to run at the pointy end of the field. Macca has done a great job for the passed 3 rounds, it would have been great to stand on the podium with him but we will have to wait until next year!''
THE WORD FROM MACAULEY “Today’s race was interesting, we have had limited laps running in the dry, only that one half hour practice session on Friday so it can make you a little hesitant as you’re still getting use to the circuit. I think I had a really good go in the start of the race and we moved forward from where we started. It was surprising to have no safety car in the race, and overall it worked out really well.” “It was great to get a top ten result today, especially after coming off the back of a couple of difficult rounds (Sandown and Bathurst) so its good to get some points on the board now. All in all we’re pretty happy.” “I’ve learned a lot from Nick in the past few rounds, its been awesome having him in the team and working alongside him has been great. It’s made me rise to another level as a driver and that’s what I want to continue to do. For me now I’ve got one round left in the Super2 Series at Newcastle and really looking forward to it.”

item.title: ITM Auckland SuperSprint
item.dc:creator: nick
item.content:encoded:
This weekend we make our annual trip to visit our Kiwi friends at the ITM Auckland SuperSprint, for the first of just two crucial single-driver events to wrap up this year’s championship.<!--more-->
This will be my fourth Supercar event at Pukekohe and I always look forward to getting to NZ, because the passion from the local fans and the atmosphere is just incredible. There’s a real amphitheatre effect in the last sector, with fans packing the hill and the grandstand to watch us slide around the last corner at 200 km/h!
Competing at this event with Brad Jones Racing means a huge amount to me, especially as I’m driving Car 8 there- the late Jason Richards’ former number.
He was a huge part of the team, and had the respect and admiration of everyone in pit lane.
We still run the JR stickers on the doors of our cars. I know we all want to represent Jason as best we can this weekend, and keep his memory alive. It would be unbelievable if either of the Tims or myself could bring back to JR Memorial trophy to Albury again. That would be as big as any Bathurst win for this team.
The format for the ITM Auckland Supersprint has changed this year, from the four shorter races in 2016 to two 70-lap races- the longest Supercars races we’ve had at Pukekohe.
I’m confident the longer races will work to our favour. We’ve found the BJR cars work well on the tyres over a longer stint, and our strength is our race pace. It looks like we could be in for more wet weather this weekend, but if the Gold Coast is anything to go by, I won’t mind if it rains! Our cars were fast in the wet … Sladey showed great pace and I was going alright too until that contact with Fabs.
Car 8 also has a new livery this event, with Harley Davidson coming on board. It’s awesome to have such an iconic brand supporting the team, and I’m really loving the flames!
Remember you can follow me on social media for updates across the weekend!

item.title: BJR WELCOMES BLACKWOODS
item.dc:creator: nick
item.content:encoded:
Brad Jones Racing and Blackwoods are excited to announce 2016 Adelaide 500 winner Nick Percat will be in Blackwoods Racing blue when he arrives at his home-town of Adelaide for round one of the 2018 Virgin Australia Supercars Championship – the Adelaide 500.
Blackwoods are proud to be on board for the always thrilling season opener, which will see Nick Percat race the Blackwoods Racing #8 ZB Commodore in front of the 200,000+ crowd that attends this stellar South Australian event every year.
Blackwoods is Australia’s leading provider of industrial supplies, with unrivalled expertise and the ability to bring together the best of the best, Blackwoods is also the first choice for BJR for all their welding, gas, tools, safety gear and PPE supplies. With all the best products from leading brands such as Milwaukee, 3M, ESAB, Lincoln and Cigweld, BJR relies on Blackwoods to help them work faster, smarter and safer in pursuit of crossing the finishing line first.
Nick Severino, Group GM – Merchandising, Blackwoods –“We’re delighted to continue to strengthen our relationship with BJR and the supercars community. The expertise of both our technical specialists and the guys at Coregas will give Nick and his team the edge in the workshop and on the track”.
Nick Percat “Not only is the Blackwoods Racing ZB Commodore my first new Supercar, it’s the first new race car I’ve had since 2007! For any driver it’s very exciting when you get to roll out a brand-new car, especially one that looks as good as this!”
“I have visited the guys and girls in the workshop a few times over the last month and they have all worked extremely hard getting these cars ready for the 2018 season. I can’t thank them enough, it’s been a huge effort.”
“It’s fantastic to have the support of Blackwoods for Adelaide. A lot of our fans would have their tool sheds filled with the quality products and safety equipment that you can not only find in the Blackwoods stores, but in the BJR workshop too!”

item.title: ADELAIDE 500
item.dc:creator: nick
item.content:encoded:
THE WORD FROM BRAD & NICK<!--more--> The Adelaide 500 proved to be a challenging weekend for 2016 winner Nick Percat and Blackwoods Racing. The qualifying result this morning meant Nick would have to work extremely hard to move forward across the 250km race in front of his home-crowd this afternoon. Whilst he managed to move forward, it was not the desired result. More from Nick and Team Boss Brad Jones below.
BRAD “Very tough weekend for the Blackwoods Racing Commodore this weekend. We’ve had an installation issue with the pedal box and the new throttle cable system that we’re running, so it was dragging a little. The guys have worked hard to fix it and had it sorted for today. We couldn’t get the car hooked up for qualifying so its made for a difficult weekend.” “When the cloud cover came over towards the end of today’s race the Blackwoods Supercar was one of the fastest cars on track. We’ll g=o home now, regroup and figure out what we need to do to go better at the Grand Prix.”
NICK “Qualifying was tough today. We needed to make a last-minute change during the session, but that meant we would only get the chance to do one flying lap. When I went out I was in the middle of a pack of cars on their fast lap, so it was unfortunate timing as I didn’t get the lap in that I should have.” “I’m happy to bring the car home straight after a difficult weekend, we’re still learning about the new ZB model. We’ve got a bit of time now to regroup before the Grand Prix so we’ll look at how we can improve the car, and work better on the hard tyres so I can push it further.”
COMING UP Australian Formula One Grand Prix Coates Hire Supercars Melbourne 400 Albert Park, Melbourne 22-25 March 2018 The first time in history this event is part of the championship! All races are for points!

item.title: COATES HIRE MELBOURNE 400 PREVIEW
item.dc:creator: nick
item.content:encoded: Hi everyone! I love the atmosphere at this time of year in Melbourne. It’s the start of the AFL season (go Adelaide Crows) and the annual Formula 1 circus heads into town. I’m pumped to get to race at the Albert Park circuit as part of the Coates Hire Melbourne 400.   It will be my fifth year at the AGP in a Supercar, but the first time racing for championship points. I think everyone is excited to finally race for points there, after so many years of it being a non-championship round. Previously racing at this event has been all about pride. Of course, I want to win anytime I’m on the track, but it’s no secret that it’s also been used as an opportunity to test new parts or setups. Now that it’s a proper race meeting, it will ensure everyone puts their best foot forward because crucial championship points are on the line. Last year’s AGP was a bit of a disaster for me. A brake caliper failed heading into turn 1 and I crashed heavily with Lee Holdsworth. I reckon it was probably the biggest crash of my career.  I went back there recently and had a look at that part of the circuit. The tyre marks and marks in the fence are still there as a reminder! Last year Brad Jones Racing overall had a lot of pace there. My teammate Tim Slade was inside the top five all weekend, so I’m confident we can run there again this year. We promised more in testing than what we delivered at the Adelaide 500, which was disappointing. On the upside … we had a bad weekend in Adelaide and still finished 11th, so I hope that when have a good weekend we can be fighting for a podium. I think we’ve got to the bottom of a few minor issues we had in Adelaide and I know there’s a lot more we’ll get out of our ZB Commodores. The format of the Coates Hire Melbourne 400 includes four short qualifying sessions- one for each race. Two of them will be held on Thursday in the twilight so the track will be cold and grippy. The next two are in the early afternoon on Friday, in peak sun and temperature so the track will be slower and require a different set up. The different track conditions could throw up some surprises in the way the field is spread, so that’s something to look forward to as well. There’s two 70 km races and two longer races that will include a compulsory pit stop. The softer compound Dunlop tyre is also in the mix, and this will add a new element of strategy that we’ve not seen before at this circuit. There’s plenty to get excited about as both a driver and a race fan! My sponsor Coates Hire always bring a huge contingent of supporters to the AGP, and I’m fortunate that I get to be involved in some cool activations throughout the race week. I can’t wait for it all to get started. You can follow me on social media for updates across the event.   Twitter- @nickpercat Instagram - @nickpercat

item.title: BACK TO BACK PODIUM FINISHES

THE WORD FROM NICK The Coates Hire Supercars Melbourne 400 wrapped up today with the final 70 km race and ANOTHER podium for Nick and the TEMPUR Racing Commodore, coming home in 2nd place.<!--more-->“It’s been a great weekend for TEMPUR Racing. We’ve managed to put some solid points on the board and getting on the podium twice, nice and early in the season is a great morale booster for everyone. item.title: CHARGE TO THE TOP TEN
item.dc:creator: nick
item.content:encoded: THE WORD FROM NICK   The times were tighter than ever at Symmons Plains, with practice sessions determining the qualifying order. Nick was only 0.05 of a second off making the top ten in practice, and only 0.035 from getting through to the second qualifying session! This saw Nick and the Blackwoods Racing Commodore start out of 17th position. Nick was one of the biggest movers of the day, through a combination of being one of the fastest cars on track and clever team strategy, Nick was able to make up a whopping 8 spots on track and finish in 9th.  This is Nick’s first top ten result ever at Symmons Plains.  NICK “We had a good strategy, and the pace we had in the Blackwoods Racing Commodore was the best it’s been all weekend. Essentially, it was the race car that we needed, but not the qualifying car we needed, we really should have qualified further forward than we did this weekend. There is just so little in the times at here Symmons Plains that you aren’t searching for tenths of a second, but hundredths, and even thousandths!”  “The Blackwoods team did a great job this weekend, and I’ve managed to get my first top ten result here at Symmons Plains. It’s not the greatest achievement but as a group we want to continue to move forward and take the little wins where we can, and hopefully we’ll be back fighting for podiums again very soon.”   CHAMPIONSHIP STANDINGS   1 – Jamie Whincup - 658 2 – Scott McLaughlin - 647 3 – David Reynolds - 647 4 – James Courtney - 624 5 – Shane Van Gisbergen – 618 8 – Nick Percat -- 505   COMING UP BJR’s 250th SUPERCARS ROUND Round 4 of the Virgin Australia Supercars Championship WD-40 Phillip Island SuperSprint 20-22 April 2018 Phillip Island, Victoria

item.title: WD40 Phillip Island 500
item.dc:creator: nick
item.content:encoded: Hi everyone! I’m looking forward to heading back to Phillip Island this weekend. It’s arguably the best permanent-built race circuit in the country with spectacular views across Bass Strait.  I feel like I’ve got a bit to sort out after a horrendous outing there last year. I was one of the many casualties of the tyre blowouts that occurred during both races. The field is back on the harder of the two tyre compounds this weekend, so hopefully that should eliminate a lot of the tyre failures that we saw last year.  This time around, my weekend goals are all about finishing the two races in respectable positions. It’s good to get back to a circuit with a fast, flowing layout and minimal kerb inputs, because this is where the BJR ZB Commodores have excelled so far this season.  This year I’m confident that we head to the Island with a package to compete well inside the top ten. I’ve had four top 10 finishes in a total of 9 Supercar races there, but I haven’t yet cracked a podium.  I’m hoping this might be the weekend for one, because it’s a pretty special event for Brad Jones Racing. The team makes its 250th championship round start, coincidentally at the same venue where BJR made its debut way back in 2000!  Brad and Kim Jones have achieved a tremendous amount over the years and I imagine if they have time to reflect on it, it’s probably pretty overwhelming. I’m honoured to be a part of their driver line-up and it would be the icing on the cake to give Brad and Kim a good result.  Car 8 has another new livery this round, with Coregas stepping up to be the major sponsor. The blue and orange colour scheme is similar to Blackwoods, as they’re part of the same family.  Overall, we’re in for an exciting event. Tyre degradation will be a factor, and it can be tricky to pass. The long, loaded corners are hard on the body, so I’ll certainly be feeling it in my neck and upper body on Monday! But again, if I can give Brad and Kim something to smile about then it will all be worth it.   Remember, you can follow me on social media for updates across the event. Twitter- @nickpercat Instagram - @nickpercat

item.title: CHARGE OF THE DAY
item.dc:creator: nick
item.content:encoded:
THE WORD FROM NICK 
The Coregas Racing Commodore suffered splitter issues again this morning, seeing Nick qualify in last position for today’s final race. The team worked quickly in between the qualifying and race session to ensure Nick wouldn’t encounter the same issues in the race. Nick worked extremely hard in the race and made a brilliant charge through the field. He was the biggest mover of the day, going from 26th to 13th! NICK “I have been getting some mega starts recently, great launch off the line and making up a few spots in the races. I think I passed about 5 cars on the first lap today! I was starting right from the back and with a couple of rookies in the field you can see they are still learning and taking it corner by corner. I was trying to think ahead of that and made moves accordingly. It was good to do a lot of passing in the Coregas Racing Commodore today.” “It was one of the hardest cars I’ve had to drive with the splitter issue; it made me work really hard and I moved around a lot in the car, so my neck and shoulders are feeling it. Qualifying this morning was pretty disappointing to have that issue arise again, and worse!” “We’ve got a lot of work to do before Perth in a couple of weeks’ time. Perth wasn’t great for us last year, so it’s been one we’ve already marked as one we need to improve on in 2018. We’ve got a few ideas we’d like to try, but it’s just taking time to implement them bit by bit. If we get a top 5 qualifying result or top 5 finish it would be as good as win for us.” “We didn’t get the chance to show the potential of the Coregas Racing Commodore this weekend which was pretty disappointing for the team. The splitter failures caused a bit of havoc as the team were under a fair amount of pressure to try solve the issues in a short amount of time. They did a great job at rising to the challenge.”   COMING UP Round 5 of the Virgin Australia Supercars Championship Perth SuperSprint Barbagallo Raceway, Perth 4-6 May 2018

item.title: PERCAT EXTENDS DEAL WITH BJR
item.dc:creator: nick
item.content:encoded:
Nick Percat has extended his driving agreement with the Brad Jones Racing team for another two years. The team is excited to confirm that this will see Nick driving with the Albury squad until at least the end of 2020.
“I am really excited to have extended my contract with Brad Jones Racing. The goal with Brad, Kim and the whole team was to fight for race wins and eventually a championship.” “My first year with BJR was character building for the whole team and I, and the way BJR continued to push and get on with the job was seriously impressive. This team is a big family, everyone has each other’s back and we all have the same goal.” The Bathurst winner joined the BJR team at the start of 2017, in what would be described as a very challenging and character building season. Fast forward to 2018, 4 rounds into the season and Nick has already produced two podium results and sits 12th in the championship. “When Brad and Kim told me they wanted to extend my contract I couldn’t have been happier. BJR is where I want to be and where I think I’ll get my best result. I know the results we have had so far this year are just the beginning, the whole team is working extremely hard to give me a winning package.” “I can’t wait to score my first race win with BJR and continue to improve the car, this will be the longest period of continuity I’ve had in my supercar career. I believe that continuity is what wins races and lets you fight for championships.” Team Boss Brad Jones added “Nick’s commitment and pace for us is unquestionable, so we’re really happy to have that stability and consistency going forward with both Nick in Car 8 and Tim Slade in the Freightliner/Alliance Truck Parts Commodore.” “I feel like Nick has grown with us in his time here already and he fits into the team really well; I can’t wait to see what we can achieve as a group over the next three years.” Nick will be in Coregas Racing colours again when the team head to Barbagallo next week for the Perth SuperSprint event.

item.title: PERTH SUPERSPRINT
item.dc:creator: nick
item.content:encoded: I’m looking forward to heading back to the west for this weekend’s Perth SuperSprint, and I’m particularly excited to get back in the car considering my recent announcement. In case you missed it, I’ve signed on to stay at Brad Jones Racing for a further two years, which means I will be with the team until the end of 2020. That will make it the longest period that I’ll have spent with one team in the main series! Together, BJR and I have scored multiple podiums and gave frequently fought at the front of the grid. I’m very comfortable and happy with the direction the team is heading in, and with Brad’s future plans. I head to Perth confident that we can continue with the car pace we’ve had this year. I’m hoping for a trouble-free weekend, after the front splitter issues we had at Phillip Island. The team has worked hard to get an all-new mounting system onto the car. They’ve also added new front bars, and together we’ve studied the data to understand why the splitter issue affected my car and not the other two. Last year in Perth wasn’t the greatest round for BJR in terms of results, although I did set the fastest lap during Saturday’s race. I feel that at least we’ve got a direction on which way to go with set up. That’s going to be really important because if the car balance isn’t right you can find yourself in a world of pain by lap five! Barbagallo Raceway has the highest rate of tyre degradation of any circuit we go to, so it will be crucial to get dialled in during practice to get a set up that looks after the tyre. We are running the new three-part qualifying format in Perth also, so Friday practice becomes more important.  The top ten fastest combined times after the final practice session will go straight into Saturday’s Q2, meaning you don’t have to make it through the first part of qualifying. The key to the Perth SuperSprint will be to have a race car that is hooked up in qualifying, but can then look after its rear tyres during the race. Maximising tyre life is something that BJR are traditionally quite strong at doing, so I’m hoping we can make it all work for a strong result! Remember, you can follow me on social media for updates across the event.

item.title: PERTH RECAP
item.dc:creator: nick
item.content:encoded:
Nick got the qualifying comeback he wanted Sunday, the 5th place practice finish boosting him into the second qualifying session; ultimately battling it out with the top ten to score a starting position of 7th for the 200km race at Barbagallo Raceway.
Nick had some good battles in the race, with the focus on tyres and a 3 or 4 pit stop strategy today. Nick crossed the line in 7th, which is his highest place finish at the Perth circuit and making it his best overall weekend at the Perth circuit.
NICK “I was happy with our qualifying efforts, the Coregas Racing Commodore really turned on this morning and its exactly what I’d been looking for.” “I think we need to look back at the race strategy today, we lost a fair amount of track time to Lowndes and Courtney who I was battling with early in the race. We should have been up there with them at the end, so we’ve missed something along the way.” “Overall we didn’t lose anything today but I just feel like the car had more in it, so it would have been good to get in the top 5 today as I really think that’s where we had the potential to be.” “We now head to the teams’ home track, Winton. It’s been a happy hunting ground there, and suits our cars, so we’re looking forward to seeing what we can do there in a couple of weeks’ time.”   COMING UP Round 6 of the Virgin Australia Supercars Championship Winton SuperSprint – BJR’s home track! 18 – 20 May Winton Motor Raceway, Victoria

wp:postmeta.wp:meta_value: Located just south of the Townsville CBD, the circuit winds its way through Reid Park where specially constructed roads form approximately 70 percent of the circuit. Set in a parkland style reminiscent of the Albert Park street circuit in Melbourne, the Townsville circuit proved to be a challenge in its inaugural year in 2009 and quickly became a favourite of the drivers.

Queensland Raceway was quickly dubbed the ‘Paperclip’ because of its six-turn design and lack of elevation. Changing temperatures can make this circuit a nightmare for drivers and engineers as its grip level changes at different times of the day. Despite its simple layout, it tends to provide entertaining racing with passing chances at turns 1, 3, 4 and 6.

Opened in 1990, the first touring car race held at Sydney Motorsport Park (then Eastern Creek International Raceway) was a 500km endurance race in the same year. SMP has a range of corners from low to high speed. Slow entry speeds to turns two and eight provide great passing opportunities.

The fast and flowing circuit laid around a horse racing track is a permanent fixture in the city. Racing the Sandown circuit is about having good power for the long runs up and down the two long straights. The fast ‘esses’ section at the end of the back straight leading into Dandenong Road Corner is one of the best sequences of corners in the Championship.

Originally constructed in 1938 as a scenic tourist drive, Mount Panorama has hosted all types of motorsport including the world famous Supercheap Auto Bathurst 1000, the annual 12 Hour GT race, 24 Hour endurance races and the Easter motorcycle meetings. The circuit is public road on non-race weekends and has also hosted the Australian Grand Prix in the past. It remains one of the all-time favourite circuits of V8 Supercar drivers and is ranked among the great race tracks of the world.

First appearing on the Australian motorsport calendar in 1991, the Gold Coast street circuit is a high speed, concrete-lined, thrill ride that was shortened for the new look event in 2010. The temporary street track has proven to create carnage in the past, particularly when drivers don’t show the patience required for victory. The Castrol Gold Coast 600 circuit sees the track cover 2.96km. The layout allows for better spectacle, providing fans with great on-track action and entertainment value. The track layout and design means is designed to reduce disruption to the local traffic and residents.

The circuit, currently 2.91 kilometres long, having been shortened from its original combined 3.5 kilometres (2.2 mi) length when combined with the now defunct club circuit and a new chicane on the back straight before the hairpin. Its visibility is low because the corridor of armco barriers is only inches from the track on both sides. It is seen as one of the fastest of all southern hemisphere. In order to win on this track, the driver needs a good entry onto the back straight. Furthermore, the driver also needs to drive the car right to its full potential.

South of Darwin, the Hidden Valley circuit features a long front straight and the second half of the lap requires a car that changes direction very well. The warm conditions mean tyre conservation and strategy will be critical to determining the race results.

The tight and twisty rural layout features a range of slow corners, which combine to make Winton the slowest circuit on the calendar. A total of 12 corners linked by short straights, the circuit was lengthened by a kilometre in 1997 with new pit garages and a new pit lane also installed.

Tough and tight, the Barbagallo circuit (formerly known as Wanneroo Raceway) was resurfaced in 2004 and initially gave very good grip. However, as the years have ticked by, the surface remains a difficult one for drivers and engineers alike. Passing opportunities are generally limited to turns six and seven under brakes, while the passing winds generally blows and onto the circuit to make life a nightmare for teams and their tyres.

Originally designed in 1956, the circuit was re-born for the 1989 Australian Motorcycle Grand Prix. The fast and flowing venue has been basically unchanged and hosts two international motorcycle events (MotoGP and World Superbikes) and a full program of national events, including the V8 Supercars Championship.

A short yet fast lap characterises Symmons Plains Raceway. The turn four hairpin and the left-hander at the end of the back straight are the two best passing opportunities. Brakes are worked hard with drivers giving them two big hits within 30 seconds of each other. The banking of the hairpin makes for a unique opportunity to line up a good run out of one of the slowest corners on the calendar.
High speed, flowing F1 style of circuit.

Shortened from its Grand Prix length by 700m to 3.2km this former Formula 1 circuit is renowned for being one of the best in the world. The circuit offers very little room for error and gives the drivers few opportunities to relax.
Inspired by some of the world’s most iconic race circuits, The Bend’s motor racing circuit is Australia’s only circuit to comply with the latest FIA Grade 2 and FIM Category A standards.

item.title: Darwin recap
item.dc:creator: nick
item.content:encoded:
THE WORD FROM NICK
Darwin turned on the heat again for our final race day here at Hidden Valley. Nick qualified in 5th, making it into the fan favorite shootout. With the UV levels at their highest the Shootout shook up the order again, with Nick being one of few cars to maintain or better their position, retaining his starting position of 5th. Whilst Macauley qualified in 25th position, keep in mind, this time is only 0.8 of a second off provisional pole sitter Scott McLaughlin. The race saw the first and only safety car of the weekend, which mixed lapped traffic with the leaders on the restart. Macauley was one of these cars and he did a great job to give the leading group the room to move forward, all at the cost of driving a lap in the marbles and burning up tyres. Macauley was one of a group of lapped cars at the finish, finishing 24th. Nick scored the fastest lap of the race, breaking the race lap record while he was at it, setting a new benchmark of 1:06.5590s. The Brad Jones Racing team sit 5th in the teams championship, with Nick just on the edge of the top ten of the drivers standings. We now have another short break before going north again… Next stop, Townsville! NICK “The Freightliner / Alliance Truck Parts Commodore continued to improve all weekend thanks to the efforts from the team, and we ticked a few boxes today with qualifying and making it into the shootout. The car balance was really good; it looked after its tyres really well and gave me what I needed today. It was a great car to drive. I didn’t realise until after the race I’d broken a new race lap record!”   COMING UP Round 8 of the Virgin Australia Supercars Championship WATPAC Townsville 400 6 – 8 July 2018 Reid Park, Townsville, QLD

item.title: Townville 400 recap
item.dc:creator: nick
item.content:encoded:
THE WORD FROM NICK
The sun shined on Townsville today for the final day of the 10th anniversary Supercars event here at the Reid Park circuit. Nick qualified 10th, which put him into the fan favourite - Top Ten Shootout. With one lap to decide the final starting order, Nick was out first and put in a flying lap, managing to go faster than both Walkinshaw Commodores to move into a starting position of 8th.
Nick had a tough start to the race and struggled for balance in the car, so the team worked quickly to make a change in his first stop on lap 24. The team opted to pit Nick earlier than planned for his second and final stop, which would mean he would do the longest stint home, 27 laps, on his Dunlop tyres. Nick fought his way home to finish in 14th, and now sits 12th in the championship. With another event in the sunshine state of Queensland in just under two weeks’ time, the team will continue on in Townsville for a couple of days to prepare the Supercars, then make their way to Brisbane for the Coates Hire Ipswich SuperSprint.   NICK “It was great to make another shootout today, it’s always a good time when you have the track to yourself, and I always talk highly of the Townsville street circuit.” “The Dunlop Supercar struggled in the race today, we tried to make a couple of changes in the first pit stop to improve the cars balance and bite, but it didn’t give me quite what I needed. It was a pretty disappointing end to the weekend, we really didn’t expect to go backwards today. We’ll be keen to go through everything from the weekend when we debrief later this week and see what we can improve on for QR in two weeks.”   COMING UP Round 9 of the Virgin Australia Supercars Championship Coates Hire Ipswich SuperSprint Queensland Raceway 20 – 22 July

item.title: COATES HIRE IPSWICH 300 RECAP
item.dc:creator: nick
item.content:encoded: THE RECAP It was a day to forget for the Summit Racing squad, with mechanical failures and bad luck ruining the chances for a good result for Nick Percat and the team today. A failed starter motor during qualifying saw Nick complete only three laps; and would see him start from a very unusual 25th position. Only two laps into the race Nick had contact with another car, with Nick coming off second-best and puncturing the left front tyre. Nick had to limp the Summit Racing Commodore back to the pits for a new tyre and to check or damaged, but the time cost in doing so put him 2 laps down. From here it was all about finishing the race and claiming any points possible. Nick finished the race where he started, in 25th.   In just under two weeks’ time the Supercars will be racing under lights at Sydney Motorsport Park. This will see a 300km race on the Saturday night, just after 7pm, and the only night race on the Supercars calendar.   THE WORD FROM NICK “Looking at the sectors we had the potential to qualify in the top ten again today, so it was a real shame for my crew and I that the starter motor failed during this mornings’ qualifying session. The guys worked frantically to try get me back out there but just didn’t have enough time.” “I knew that we would have to work hard in the race to pass a lot of cars and move forward, but we got a puncture on the second lap of the race. I had to get the Summit Racing Commodore all the way back into the pits for the guys to change the tyre and they had to check for any damaged steering whilst I was there. The extra stop sent me a lap down, so from there we just looked to use old tyres so we could save a couple of the green tyres for a later date. It was disappointing for the guys, and not where we wanted to finish in the Summit Racing Commodore.”   WHERE TO NEXT… Round 10 of the Virgin Australia Supercars Championship Red Rooster Sydney SuperNight 300 3 -4 August 2018 Sydney Motorsport Park, Eastern Creek   CHAMPIONSHIP STANDINGS 1 – Scott McLaughlin - 2321 2 – Shane Van Gisbergen - 2190 3 – Jamie Whincup - 1870 4 – David Reynolds - 1838 5 – Craig Lowndes - 1821 11 – Nick Percat - 1330

item.title: The Bend - Recap
item.dc:creator: nick
item.content:encoded:
THE RECAP & WORD FROM NICK
Nick Percat put on show in the X Convenience Mobil Supercar today, powering through the field from 15th to 5th. Nick was one of the fastest Supercars on track today, undoubtedly proving that through his charge forward. The X Convenience Mobil garage erupted in cheers many times as some great passing moves were made by Nick. He and team-mate Tim Slade finished in 4th and 5th respectively, moving them further up the team’s championship – now sitting 3rd behind Red Bull Racing Holden Team and Dick Johnson Racing Team Penske. For wild-card Macauley Jones he had another very respectable result today, qualifying in 20th, and finishing in 19th. The team put in a stellar effort to be the only ZB Commodore wild card entry for 2018, getting invaluable experience for the endurance season ahead.   The team will now return to Albury, where they will prepare for a test day in less than two weeks’ time, then head to Sandown for the first of the endurance events.   NICK “We made a really strong recovery in the X Convenience Mobil Supercar after qualifying poorly today. The crew did a great job with the setup and gave me a strong race car. It was fast in clean air and gave me a lot of confidence to push, and therefore I had some pretty good battles passing people out on track today.”   “Good strategy by the team to pit how we did, the middle stint was quite short, and for both the X Convenience Mobil and Freightliner Racing Commodores of Tim and I to have a top five finish was a great result. Hopefully we can continue this momentum heading into the endurance events.”   “My co-driver Macauley had a solid weekend, he out-qualified some top names in the field and did a great job to finish inside the top twenty today. It’s certainly not an easy task to take on the field at any event, let alone a brand new one. He’s really held his own this weekend and I look forward to seeing what we can achieve together at the upcoming endurance events.”   COMING UP Round 12 of the Virgin Australia Supercars Championship & Event 1 of 3 of the Pirtek Endurance Cup The RABBLE.club Sandown 500 14 – 16 September 2018 Sandown Raceway, Melbourne CHAMPIONSHIP POINTS 1 – Shane Van Gisbergen – 2778 2 – Scott McLaughlin - 2759 3 – Jamie Whincup - 2416 4 – Craig Lowndes - 2229 5 – David Reynolds - 2213 11 – Nick Percat - 1693

item.title: PERTH - RECAP
item.dc:creator: nick
item.content:encoded:
Saturday 4th May
Qualifying Qualified: 9th Pole Position: Scott McLaughlin Race Twelve – 200kms / 83 Laps Finished: 10th Winner: Scott McLaughlin   RECAP Fireworks were expected on and off the track at Barbagallo Raceway as fans lined the banks of the circuit, ready to see the spectacular lights and sounds of Supercars as they take on the final Perth night race. For drivers, the 200km battle under lights was their last chance to put on a show and fight for a podium finish. Nick drove the Holden Guaranteed Value Supercar to 7th in the final practice session, again earning his place in the second qualifying session. Continuing the consistent fast form, he qualified in 9th position. After the huge fireworks and light show, the 200km night fight was underway. Nick found himself trading places early in the race, gaining a couple of spots. Nick pitted on lap 49, just before the one and only safety car appearance of the race. Any remaining drivers who hadn’t made their stops dived into the lane to make their final stop; then it was a race to the finish. After a slow stop, Nick rejoined in 12th, and fought his way back into 10th where he finished. The top ten streak now sits at 8, with Nick 8th in the championship and Brad Jones Racing are 3rd in the teams championship. Next up the Holden team head to their home circuit, Winton Motor Raceway for their their second test day of 2019 and then back there again for the next round of the championship on the 24-26 of May.   THE WORD FROM NICK “The Holden Guaranteed Value Supercar has had great one lap pace this weekend which is something we have been working hard to improve at BJR. It’s a credit to the team and my engineer Andrew for turning it around after Thursday night.” “It has been great to have the Holden Lion on the doors this weekend, the #8 Commodore looks so good under lights and has brought back a lot of memories for the Holden fans with Skaife, Lowndes, and myself with Bathurst and having so much family history with the brand. It’s been really well received by the fans.” “It was awesome to continue our top ten finishing streak here in Perth. The guys were pressed to reset the back to back pit stops for both the BJR cars so we lost a few seconds in the stop. It’s one of those unfortunate things that can happen, but we stayed inside the ten. The guys have worked really hard this weekend and gave me a pretty speedy rocket in the Holden Guaranteed Value Supercar. I’m looking forward to seeing what we can do at our home track (Winton) in a few weeks time.”   CHAMPIONSHIP POINTS 1 – Scott McLaughlin - 1346 2 – Fabian Coulthard - 1204 3 – Shane Van Gisbergen - 1024 4 – David Reynolds - 971 5 – Chaz Mostert - 944 8 – Nick Percat - 877   COMING UP Round 6 of the Virgin Australia Supercars Championship Truck Assist Winton SuperSprint Winton Motor Raceway, Benalla, Victoria 24-26 May 2019

item.title: Samantha Smith
item.dc:creator: jarome
item.content:encoded: Say what you want about having 5 amazing sliders or 1,000+ layout shortcodes.. This template just works, and it works super fast. I'm taking that over bloatware any day of the week!

item.title: Joshua Sparks
item.dc:creator: jarome
item.content:encoded: Hmmm... Wow! I've been working with a lot of templates, but i was pleasantly surprised with this one. The amount of CSS is minimal, and very well organised. Nice!
